ANAPLASMOSIS - GERMANY (02): BACKGROUND
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sun 20 Apr 2014
Source: Gideon [edited]
http://www.gideononline.com


The following data on anaplasmosis in Germany are abstracted from the Gideon e-book series [1,2] (primary references available on request).

Prevalence surveys:
- 5.3 percent of rodents and one percent of _Ixodes ricinus_ in Stuttgart (2008 publication)
- 3.2 percent of _Ixodes ricinus_ adults and 2.3 percent of nymphs. 0.9 percent of infected ticks were also found to carry _Borrelia spp_ (Hanover, 2011 publication)
- 61.8 percent of blood samples from European hedgehogs (_Erinaceus europaeus_), 73.4 percent of associated _Ixodes ricinus_ and 26.6 percent of _Ixodes hexagonus_ (2007 to 2008)
- 3.2 percent of bird-feeding and 1.1 percent of rodent-feeding ticks in central Germany (2007)
- 1.4 percent of bird-feeding _Ixodes ricinus_ in middle Germany (2007)
- 2.6 percent of bird-feeding _Ixodes ricinus_ on a conservation island in the Baltic Sea (2007)
- 2.6 percent of _Ixodes ricinus_ ticks from wild birds in the Baltic region (2007)
- 4.5 percent of hard ticks in Hanover (2010)
- 3.6 percent of _Ixodes ricinus_ in Hamburg (2011)
- 1.0 percent of _Ixodes ricinus_ collected from vegetation on the Baltic coast (2008)
- 2.9 percent of questing _Ixodes ricinus_ in Bavaria (2006)
- 8.7 percent of questing _Ixodes ricinus_ in Leipzig (2009)
- 11.6 percent / 13.3 percent of adult female / male _Ixodes ricinus_ females/males in Bavarian public parks in 2009; 8.5 percent / 9.2 percent in 2010
- 0 percent of questing adult _Dermacentor reticulatus_ ticks in the outskirts of Berlin (2012 publication)
- 8.2 percent of red foxes (_Vulpes vulpes_) and 23 percent of raccoon dogs (_Nyctereutes procyonoides_) in Brandenburg (2014 publication)
- 98.9 percent of roe deer (_Capreolus capreolus_) and 86.1 percent of engorged deer ticks (Bavaria, 2010 to 2012)

Seroprevalence surveys:
- 14.0 percent of forestry workers, 11.4 percent of Lyme disease patients, and 1.9 percent of blood donors in southern Germany (1983 to 1984)
- 5.5 percent of persons in the Rhine-Main area including 13.1 percent of patients with Lyme disease in the same region (1999 publication)
- 4.9 percent military personnel in southwestern Germany
- 15 percent of hunters in Styria and Burgenland (2003 publication)
- 4.5 percent of persons seropositive toward _Borrelia burgdorferi_ and 1.2 percent of seronegatives (Berlin/Brandenburg, 1994 to 2001)
- 50.1 percent of dogs under investigation for anaplasmosis (2006 publication)
- 19.4 percent of dogs in Munich (2012 publication)
- 43 percent of dogs in northeast Germany (2010 publication)
- 17.8 percent of imported and traveling dogs (2010 publication)
- 43.2 percent of symptomatic and asymptomatic dogs (2007 publication)
- 43.2 percent of hunting dogs in Baden-Wurttemberg region (2007)
- 16.2 percent of cats in Bavaria and Lower Saxony (2012 publication)
- 9.1 percent of cats in Berlin / Brandenburg (2012 publication)

References:
1. Berger SA: Infectious Diseases of Germany, 2014. 565 pages, 148 graphs, 3,318 references. Gideon e-books, http://www.gideononline.com/ebooks/country/infectious-diseases-of-germany/.
2. Berger SA: Anaplasmosis: Global Status, 2014. 33 pages, 545 references. Gideon e-books, http://www.gideononline.com/ebooks/disease/anaplasmosis-global-status/.

